    <script is:inline type="application/ld+json">
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "@id": "https://mrlawassociates.com/#faq",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I choose the best family lawyer in Karachi?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Look for a lawyer who focuses on family law rather than general practice, check that they are enrolled with the Sindh Bar Council, and ask about their experience with cases like yours, whether that's khula, custody, or maintenance. Many women feel more comfortable with a female advocate for sensitive matters. Use the first free consultation to see how clearly they explain things and how comfortable you feel with them."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does a family lawyer in Karachi cost?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Every family matter is different, so the fee depends on the type of case, how complex it is, and how many connected claims are involved. We talk it through openly and honestly before you commit to anything, with no hidden charges. Your first consultation is free, so please call 0336 3120798 to discuss your specific matter in confidence."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can a wife get khula without her husband's consent?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Under Pakistani law a wife can obtain khula through the Family Court without her husband's consent. The 2015 amendment to the Family Courts Act strengthened this right. Even if the husband refuses to attend, the court can proceed and dissolve the marriage. Khula usually involves returning or waiving the dower, and we guide you through every step so you understand exactly what to expect."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How long does a family case take in Karachi?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It varies with the type of case. An uncontested khula often concludes in 3 to 6 months, while a contested divorce can take 6 to 18 months. Custody matters usually take 4 to 12 months, and interim relief like a visitation schedule can start much sooner. Our office sits right beside the City Court, which helps us file and move your case quickly."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Should I hire a female lawyer for family law matters?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Many women in Pakistan feel more comfortable discussing sensitive family matters with a female lawyer. Advocate Reema Jawed provides culturally appropriate representation while ensuring your legal rights are fully protected in divorce, khula, child custody, and maintenance cases. Her female-led practice offers a safe environment for clients to discuss personal issues."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Who gets child custody after divorce in Karachi?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Custody follows the welfare of the child. Under Islamic law, mothers usually keep custody of boys until about age 7 and girls until puberty, and courts can extend this where it serves the child. The father stays financially responsible whoever has custody, and the other parent keeps visitation rights. We help you protect both your bond with your children and their support."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can overseas Pakistanis handle a divorce or custody case in Karachi without visiting?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Through a Special Power of Attorney, attested at the Pakistani Embassy or Consulate where you live, we can represent you in the Karachi Family Courts without you flying back for hearings. We handle divorce, khula, custody, and maintenance matters on your behalf, and your first consultation can happen over a call or video meeting, whatever feels comfortable."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can the court protect me from domestic violence during my case?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Alongside a divorce, khula, or maintenance case, the court can pass protection and residence orders so an abusive husband cannot harass you or throw you out of the home. If you have faced violence or threats, please keep any medical reports, messages, or photos, because that evidence helps us secure faster protection for you and your children. A female advocate handles this with the care it deserves."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
    </script>
